        description:
            'Rusty the fox loved sunbeams more than anything in the world. He loved the way they slanted through the leaves in the morning, warm and gold and full of dancing dust. So he decided to collect them.\n\nHe cupped them in his paws — they slipped away.\nHe tried carrying them in a basket of leaves — they seeped through.\nHe dug a hole in the ground and tried to keep one there — gone by nightfall.\n\nRusty sat in his cold, dark den feeling very sad.\n\nThen his neighbour, a small hedgehog, poked her nose in.\n\n"What is wrong?"\n\n"Sunbeams won\'t stay," Rusty sighed.\n\nThe hedgehog thought for a moment. "Maybe they\'re not meant to stay. Maybe they\'re meant to be shared."\n\nThe next morning, Rusty woke up early and went to find his friends. One by one, he brought them to the sunniest spots in the forest — the clearing where the light fell warmest, the stone by the stream where it sparkled most.\n\nAnd as his friends lifted their faces to the light and smiled, Rusty felt something warm and golden settle right in the middle of his chest — and stay there.',
