        description:
            'Oliver the owl was reading his favourite book by moonlight when something small and bright fell out of the sky and landed with a soft thud in the branches above him.\n\nHe climbed up to look. Curled on a branch, trembling, was a tiny star — no bigger than a fist — with a pale flicker where her glow should have been.\n\n"I fell," she said in a small voice. "I was trying to find my place in the sky, and I got lost, and then I fell."\n\nOliver adjusted his spectacles. "Which constellation do you belong to?"\n\n"The Little Dipper," she whispered. "But I can\'t find it anymore."\n\nOliver thought carefully. Then he carried her to the very top of the tallest tree, where the view was clear and wide and full of sky.\n\n"Look north," he said. "Follow the two bright stars that point upward. Do you see?"\n\nThe tiny star looked. She saw a familiar flicker far above.\n\n"That\'s home," she breathed.\n\nAnd with one small, brave leap, she flew upward — growing brighter and brighter — until she clicked back into her place in the Little Dipper like a key in a lock.\n\nOliver watched from his branch, satisfied, and went back to his book.',
