        description:
            'Deep in the ancient forest stood Grandmother Willow — the oldest tree anyone could remember. Her long branches swept the ground like gentle arms, and if you sat very still beneath her, you could hear her whisper.\n\nAnimals came from far away to sit with her. A young fox came when he felt lost. Two arguing birds came when they could not agree. A little deer came simply because she felt sad and did not know why.\n\nGrandmother Willow never rushed. She never shouted. She just whispered — slowly, in the language of leaves and wind and rain.\n\n"Grow your roots deep, and the storms will not break you."\n\n"Rest in the winter. Bloom in the spring. You cannot always be doing."\n\n"Quiet is not empty. Sometimes quiet is full of everything."\n\nThe animals did not always understand her words right away. But they always left feeling calmer — as if just sitting beneath her had untangled something inside them.\n\nSome evenings, Grandmother Willow whispered to no one at all. Just in case anyone was listening.',
