            'On the day Emma moved to a new town, her grandmother pressed something into her hands — a small wooden box, worn smooth with age, with a tiny brass key on the side.\n\n"Wind it up when you feel lonely," her grandmother said.\n\nThat first evening, in her bare new room with no pictures on the walls and no familiar sounds outside, Emma wound the key.\n\nThe music began — soft and sweet and spinning.\n\nAnd then, one by one, tiny golden fireflies floated out from the box, dancing slowly in the air around her. They moved in patterns — like two children chasing each other, like a family sitting together at a table, like a little girl waving hello to a neighbour.\n\nEmma watched them for a long time.\n\nThe music slowed. The fireflies drifted back.\n\nBut something had changed. The room felt less empty. The town outside felt less strange.\n\nShe wound the box every evening for a week. And then one day, a girl from next door knocked on her door, having heard the music through the window.\n\n"That\'s lovely," said the girl. "Can I hear it too?"\n\nEmma smiled and moved over to make room.',
