      Story(
        id: '22',
        title: 'The Sleepy Sloth',
        category: 'Animals',
        description:
            'Sammy the sloth moved slowly. Not a little slowly — very, very slowly.\n\nWhile other animals rushed through the jungle, Sammy hung from his branch and watched the light change through the leaves. While the monkeys raced and the parrots chattered and the jaguars prowled at speed, Sammy moved one careful arm at a time.\n\n"Lazy!" the monkeys called, whizzing past.\n\nSammy just blinked.\n\nThen the great storm came. Three days of thunder and lashing rain that broke branches and flooded paths and blew the toucans\' nests to pieces. When it finally stopped, every animal was exhausted. They had used all their rushing energy just to survive.\n\nBut Sammy was rested.\n\nSlowly, steadily, he helped the toucans rebuild their nest. He carried a small lost armadillo to safety. He brought fruit to the tired monkeys, one piece at a time.\n\n"How are you not tired?" a monkey asked, panting.\n\n"I save my energy," Sammy said, quite simply.\n\nThe jungle was quiet for a moment.\n\nThen the monkey nodded — slowly, for once — and helped Sammy carry the next branch.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.8,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/Sleepy Sloth.jpeg',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['acceptance', 'patience', 'jungle'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '23',
        title: 'The Comet and the Lonely Planet',
        category: 'Space',
        description:
            'Far out at the cold edge of the solar system, where the sun looked no bigger than a bright star, Planet Pluto floated alone.\n\nOther planets had neighbours and moons and passing spacecraft. But no one came this far. The days were long and very quiet.\n\nThen one morning, Pluto noticed something streak across the distant dark — a blazing, tumbling comet with a tail like a silver scarf.\n\n"Hello!" Pluto called out, not expecting an answer.\n\nBut the comet stopped.\n\n"Hello yourself," said Charlie the Comet. "I haven\'t seen another world out this far in ages."\n\nHe stayed for a while — long enough to tell Pluto about the rings of Saturn, the storms of Jupiter, and a little blue planet full of oceans and birds and people who looked up at the night sky and wondered.\n\nWhen Charlie had to leave, he promised to come back.\n\n"My orbit takes about 75 years," he said apologetically.\n\n"That\'s all right," said Pluto. "I\'ll be here."\n\nAnd though the skies were dark and quiet again, Pluto noticed they felt different now. Not quite so empty. Not quite so alone.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Comet and the Lonely Planet.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['friendship', 'space', 'loneliness'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '24',
        title: 'The Firefly Who Lost Her Light',
        category: 'Moral Stories',
        description:
            'One morning Fiona the firefly woke up and knew immediately that something was wrong.\n\nShe tried to glow. Nothing.\n\nShe shook herself. Still nothing.\n\nShe looked at her reflection in a dewdrop — just a small, ordinary insect, no light at all.\n\nFeeling hollow, she wandered into the forest. She didn\'t feel like helping anyone — but when she saw a little beetle going round and round in circles, lost and confused, she quietly guided him home.\n\nA flicker. Just a tiny one.\n\nThen she found a caterpillar, scared and shivering in the open. She sat with it and told it a slow, soft story until it calmed down and crept to safety.\n\nA warm glow, very small.\n\nShe shared the last of her food with a family of ants carrying too heavy a load.\n\nThe glow grew.\n\nBy evening, walking home through the tall grass, Fiona looked down at herself and saw that she was shining — not a fierce blaze, but a steady, warm, trusting light.\n\nShe had not found her glow by searching for it.\n\nShe had found it by giving it away.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Firefly Who Lost Her Light.jpeg',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['kindness', 'inner-light', 'helping'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '25',
        title: 'The Little Lighthouse',
        category: 'Adventures',
        description:
            'Leo was the smallest lighthouse on the coast. His beam was not the brightest, and he was not the tallest. The big lighthouses could be seen for many miles — Leo\'s light reached only a little way.\n\nSome nights he felt quite useless.\n\nBut on one particular night, a thick fog rolled in off the sea — so thick that the great lighthouses could not cut through it. Their powerful beams scattered and blurred.\n\nThe ships called out in the dark. Nothing.\n\nLeo kept his small light going. Just steady and calm — on, off, on, off.\n\nAnd because Leo stood lower than the others, his beam ran just below the fog, right at water level — right where the lost boats could see it.\n\nOne by one, following Leo\'s small, faithful light, the boats found the harbour.\n\nThe harbour master came to Leo the next morning.\n\n"How?" he asked.\n\nLeo thought for a moment. "I just kept going," he said simply. "I didn\'t know what else to do."\n\nThe harbour master smiled. "That," he said, "is exactly enough."',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.8,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Little Lighthouse.jpg',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['purpose', 'helping', 'ocean'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '26',
        title: 'The Elephant Who Painted Dreams',
        category: 'Magical World',
        description:
            'Ellie the elephant discovered her gift quite by accident.\n\nOne evening she lifted her trunk to smell the night air, and a swirl of colour came out — soft blue and golden yellow, curling up into the sky like smoke from a slow fire. It drifted higher and spread into shapes: a friendly whale, a forest of silver trees, a boat on a calm sea.\n\nIn the valley below, children pressed their faces to their windows and watched, then went to bed and dreamed the most beautiful dreams.\n\nSo every night, Ellie painted. She worked for hours, making dream after dream, sky painting after sky painting — until one morning she woke up with dark rings under her eyes and a heavy heart, and realised she had not dreamed herself in a very long time.\n\nThe Moon noticed.\n\n"You give dreams to others," the Moon said. "But you are a dreamer too, Ellie. Rest. Let the sky be empty for one night."\n\nEllie hesitated. Then she lay down on the soft earth, closed her eyes, and let herself go.\n\nThe dream that came was the most wonderful she had ever made.',
        duration: 5,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Elephant Who Painted Dreams.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['creativity', 'dreams', 'art'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '27',
        title: 'The Cricket and the Silent Night',
        category: 'Nature',
        description:
            'Chirpy the cricket sang every night without fail. As soon as the sun dipped below the hills, he rubbed his wings together and filled the air with his bright, steady song.\n\nOne evening he wondered: what would happen if he stopped?\n\nSo he stayed quiet.\n\nAt first — nothing. Just dark. Then, very slowly, he began to hear things he had never noticed before. Another cricket, far away, chirping in a slightly different rhythm. The soft rustle of a mouse in the long grass. An owl calling from the forest. Leaves chattering in the wind. The stream, far below, talking quietly to itself.\n\nThe whole night was singing.\n\nHe had just never heard it because he had been so busy singing himself.\n\nWhen Chirpy began again, he played differently — softer sometimes, faster in some places, with little pauses left open like windows. And from out of the dark, other sounds came to fill them: the frog\'s deep note, the wind\'s long hum, the rustling leaves.\n\nIt was, Chirpy thought, the best music he had ever made.\n\nAnd he had not made it alone.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Cricket and the silent Night.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['music', 'comfort', 'nature'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '28',
        title: 'The Snowy Owl and the Northern Lights',
        category: 'Nature',
        description:
            'Aurora the snowy owl lived in the far north, where the winters were long and the sky was full of wonder. On the clearest nights, the Northern Lights came — great ribbons of green and purple and pink, dancing silently across the black sky.\n\nAurora loved to fly through them.\n\nShe spread her wide white wings and rose up into the light. And something extraordinary happened — the lights bent around her, shifted and shimmered, as if dancing with her rather than just past her.\n\nLittle animals watching from below gasped.\n\nBecause Aurora\'s white feathers caught the colour and sent it spinning outward in ripples, so that the sky was more beautiful than it had ever been — not just lights, but lights and wings together.\n\nOne small fox called up to her: "Aurora! You make them brighter!"\n\nAurora swooped low and tilted her head.\n\n"No," she said quietly. "They make me brighter. And together — well, together we make something that neither of us could make alone."\n\nShe rose again into the sky, and the lights wrapped around her, and the valley below was filled with colour and quiet wonder.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Snowy Owl and the Northern Lights.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['wonder', 'nature', 'magic'],
        isFeatured: true,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '29',
        title: 'The Caterpillar Who Was Afraid to Change',
        category: 'Moral Stories',
        description:
            'Cami the caterpillar loved her life exactly as it was.\n\nShe loved the big green leaf she called home. She loved the way the morning dew tasted. She loved her soft, many-legged walk through the garden. She did not want any of it to change.\n\nBut one day she felt a strange pull — like something inside her was ready, even if she was not.\n\n"It\'s time," said a kind old butterfly resting nearby.\n\n"But what if I don\'t like being a butterfly?" Cami asked.\n\n"You might not like the change," the butterfly said gently. "But you will like who you become."\n\nCami thought for a long time. Then, very slowly, she began to spin.\n\nInside her cocoon it was dark and strange and nothing like a green leaf. But she waited. And grew.\n\nWhen she finally pushed her way out into the light, she stretched wings she had never had before — wide, patterned, made for sky.\n\nShe looked back at the green leaf and thought how small it seemed now. Then she lifted off, and the world opened up below her like a gift.\n\nChange, she thought, was the most terrifying and most wonderful thing that had ever happened to her.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Caterpillar Who Was Afraid to Change.webp',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['change', 'growth', 'courage'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '30',
        title: 'The Starfish and the Gentle Tide',
        category: 'Nature',
        description:
            'Stella the starfish was exhausted.\n\nEvery day the tide came and went, and every day Stella gripped the rock with all five arms and fought it. She would not be moved. She would not be carried. She stayed exactly where she was, and it took all the energy she had.\n\nOne afternoon, too tired to hold on, she let go.\n\nThe wave picked her up gently — not roughly, not harshly, but the way you might carry something precious. It moved her along warm, shallow water, past a garden of purple sea anemones she had never seen, over a reef where tiny fish darted like sparks.\n\nAnd then, as the tide turned, it brought her back — setting her down in a quiet rock pool, safe and warm and still.\n\nStella looked around at the rock pool. It was beautiful.\n\nShe had been fighting the tide her whole life, and this whole time it had only wanted to show her something lovely.\n\nShe loosened her grip on the rock — just a little.\n\nAnd she waited, with open arms, for the next wave.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Starfish and The Gentle Tide.jpg',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['peace', 'ocean', 'rhythm'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '31',
        title: 'The Sleepy Train to Dreamland',
        category: 'Adventures',
        description:
            'Every night, just as the last light went out in the last bedroom window, a train appeared.\n\nNo one knew exactly where it came from. It arrived very quietly — just a soft choo-choo and a warm glow on the tracks — and stopped at the edge of every town and village and city in the world, all at once.\n\nChildren who were almost asleep found themselves in pyjamas on the platform, clutching their stuffed animals and their favourite blankets.\n\nThey climbed aboard.\n\nThe seats were the softest imaginable — like sitting in a cloud. The conductor, a round and twinkly-eyed rabbit, brought warm milk and biscuits. Outside the windows, the world turned into something else entirely: Candy Cloud Canyon, where the sky was pink and tasted of strawberries. Snoring Mountain, where the whole mountain rumbled gently like a sleeping giant. The River of Dreams, where the water was silver and caught the moonlight like a mirror.\n\nBy the time the train arrived at its final stop — each child\'s own perfect dream — every passenger was already fast asleep.\n\nThe conductor tucked them in, one by one.\n\nThen the train moved quietly on into the night.',
        duration: 5,
        rating: 4.8,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Sleepy Train to Dreamland.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['dreams', 'adventure', 'sleep'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '32',
        title: 'The Hummingbird Who Shared Joy',
        category: 'Animals',
        description:
            'Holly the hummingbird moved through the world like a tiny living spark — a flash of emerald and ruby, gone before you could look properly.\n\nBut wherever Holly went, things changed.\n\nShe hovered by a sick sparrow who had not left his branch in three days, and sang to him in the small buzzing language of hummingbirds until he blinked and ruffled his feathers for the first time in days.\n\nShe found a baby bird trying and failing to fly, and flew beside her — slowly, impossibly slowly for a hummingbird — showing her the way.\n\nShe carried a single bright petal to the darkest corner of the garden, where the shade plants grew, and left it there like a tiny gift.\n\nNo one asked Holly why she did these things. She didn\'t have an answer anyway. It just felt like the right way to move through the world — to leave things slightly better than you found them.\n\nAnd somehow, in every place Holly had visited, the flowers grew a little brighter, and the birdsong carried a little further, and the whole garden felt more alive.\n\nHolly hummed to herself and moved on to the next thing.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.8,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/Hummingbird Who Shared Joy.jpeg',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['joy', 'sharing', 'happiness'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '33',
        title: 'The Rainbow After the Storm',
        category: 'Nature',
        description:
            'The storm came fast and loud.\n\nThunder cracked over the forest. Lightning split the sky. The rain fell so hard it sounded like a hundred rivers all at once. Every animal hid — the rabbits in their burrows, the birds pressed into their nests, the deer tucked under the great old pine.\n\nThe little hedgehog curled into the tightest ball she could and tried very hard to be brave.\n\nAnd then — silence.\n\nFirst just the dripping of leaves. Then birdsong, one careful note at a time. Then a patch of pale sky, then a wider one.\n\nThen — colour.\n\nIt began at the edge of the meadow and stretched and stretched until it arched all the way across the whole sky, end to end: red, orange, yellow, green, blue, violet — each colour soft and perfectly placed, like someone had painted it there on purpose.\n\nThe hedgehog uncurled. Her eyes went wide.\n\nOne by one the animals came out to look. No one spoke for a while. They just stood together in the wet grass and looked up.\n\n"The storm made it possible," said the old oak tree quietly.\n\nAnd every creature in the forest understood.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Rainbow After the Storm.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['hope', 'beauty', 'nature'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '34',
        title: 'The Bedtime Knight',
        category: 'Fairy Tales',
        description:
            'Sir Snooze was not like other knights.\n\nHe carried no sword. His armour was woven from moonlight and his shield was made from the softest, most peaceful thoughts in the whole kingdom. Instead of a horse, he rode a gentle cloud that drifted quietly through the night air without making a sound.\n\nEvery evening at bedtime, Sir Snooze began his rounds.\n\nHe floated past one house and sent a bad dream packing with just a firm look. He drifted past another and let in a good dream — a dream of swimming, of flying, of a warm kitchen smelling of something wonderful.\n\nAt each window, he paused and listened.\n\nIf a child was still awake, he would hum — very softly, just below hearing — the kind of hum that sounded like a lullaby you couldn\'t quite remember but somehow already knew.\n\nBy midnight, every window in the kingdom was dark.\n\nSir Snooze settled on a rooftop and waited, watching quietly as the whole world slept — tucked in and safe and dreaming — and felt, as he always did, that this was the most important job in all the land.',
        duration: 5,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/Bedtime Knight.jpeg',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['protection', 'dreams', 'bravery'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '35',
        title: 'The Wise Owl and the Worried Rabbit',
        category: 'Moral Stories',
        description:
            'Riley the rabbit worried about everything.\n\nShe worried about rain when the sky was clear, and about clear skies making the grass too dry. She worried about what she would eat tomorrow, and whether her burrow was deep enough, and whether the fox she hadn\'t seen in weeks might come back.\n\nShe was so busy worrying that she forgot to eat her supper, and the moon rose and she hadn\'t noticed the day go by at all.\n\nThe wise old owl found her sitting in the meadow with her ears flat against her head.\n\n"What worries you, Riley?" he asked gently.\n\nRiley listed everything. It took quite a long time.\n\nWhen she finished, the owl was quiet for a moment. Then he said: "Put your paws on the ground."\n\nShe did.\n\n"Feel the grass. Is it soft?"\n\n"Yes."\n\n"Is the air warm?"\n\n"Yes."\n\n"Are you safe, right now, in this moment?"\n\nRiley paused. She looked around. Stars overhead. Soft ground beneath. The owl beside her.\n\n"Yes," she said quietly.\n\n"Then stay here for a while," said the owl. "Tomorrow\'s worries can wait until tomorrow."\n\nRiley breathed out slowly. And for the first time in a long while, she just sat — and it was enough.',
        duration: 4,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Wise Owl and The Worried Rabbit.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['wisdom', 'worry', 'peace'],
        isFeatured: true,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '39',
        title: 'Little Red Riding Hood',
        category: 'Fairy Tales',
        description:
            'One morning, Little Red Riding Hood packed a basket with warm bread, honey, and flowers, and set off through the forest to visit her grandmother, who had not been feeling well.\n\n"Stay on the path," her mother reminded her. "And do not talk to strangers."\n\nThe forest was beautiful and dappled with light. But partway through, she met a wolf who smiled too widely and asked too many questions. She told him more than she should have.\n\nThe wolf ran ahead by a faster route and arrived at Grandmother\'s house first. When Red Riding Hood knocked and entered, something felt wrong. The voice was strange. The eyes were strange. Everything was strange.\n\n"Grandmother — what big eyes you have!"\n\n"All the better to see you with."\n\n"What big ears!"\n\n"All the better to hear you with."\n\n"What big teeth!"\n\n"All the better to—"\n\nA woodcutter who had been passing heard the commotion and burst through the door, and the wolf ran away and was never seen in that part of the forest again. Grandmother was found safe in the cupboard, a little shaken but unhurt.\n\nOn the walk home, Red Riding Hood held the woodcutter\'s hand and thought carefully about what it meant to be clever, as well as kind.',
        duration: 5,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Red Riding Hood.jpg',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['adventure', 'bravery', 'safety'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '40',
        title: 'The Little Mermaid',
        category: 'Fairy Tales',
        description:
            'Deep beneath the ocean, in a palace of coral and pearl, lived a young mermaid princess named Ariel. She had a beautiful voice and a curiosity about the world above the water that never left her.\n\nOne stormy night, she watched a ship break apart in the waves and dove through the dark water to save a young prince from drowning. She brought him to shore and sat with him until he breathed again, then slipped away before he opened his eyes.\n\nShe could not stop thinking about him.\n\nIn desperation, she made a bargain with the sea witch — her voice in exchange for legs and three days on land to win the prince\'s heart. Without her voice, she could only smile and hope he would understand.\n\nThe witch nearly won. But love — and the courage of a small crab and a faithful fish — helped the truth come through. When the prince understood what Ariel had given up for him, his heart knew what it had always known.\n\nAriel\'s father, seeing his daughter\'s love was real and true, transformed her with a blessing rather than a curse.\n\nShe rose from the sea on two feet and walked toward the prince, and the ocean cheered behind her.',
        duration: 6,
        rating: 5.0,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Little Mermaid.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['love', 'courage', 'dreams'],
        isFeatured: true,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '41',
        title: 'Beauty and the Beast',
        category: 'Fairy Tales',
        description:
            'When Belle\'s father stumbled into an enchanted castle during a storm and was imprisoned by the fearsome Beast within, Belle made the only choice her heart would allow: she took her father\'s place.\n\nThe castle was grand but cold, and the Beast was frightening at first — loud and sharp and surrounded by shadows. But Belle was not easily frightened.\n\nShe noticed things. The way he carefully set out her meals. The way he gave her the library without being asked. The way he stood at the window on cold nights, looking out, as if waiting for something he had given up hoping for.\n\nSlowly, carefully, they began to talk.\n\nAnd Belle found that beneath the fur and the fangs was someone who was lonely and ashamed, who had been unkind long ago and had spent years paying for it.\n\nThe night she told him she cared for him — truly, without being asked — the castle shook with light. The curse that had held him for so long broke apart like ice in spring.\n\nThe prince he had once been stood before her — but Belle found she loved him no better and no worse than she had the moment before.\n\nBecause she had always been looking at who he really was.',
        duration: 6,
        rating: 5.0,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/The Cursed Prince.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['kindness', 'true love', 'magic'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '42',
        title: 'Rapunzel',
        category: 'Fairy Tales',
        description:
            'At the top of a tall stone tower, with no door and no stairs, lived a girl named Rapunzel. Her golden hair was so long and so strong that the witch who had raised her used it as a ladder — calling up each evening, and Rapunzel would let it fall.\n\nRapunzel had never questioned this. It was simply the way things were.\n\nUntil the evening a voice called up that was not the witch\'s.\n\nA young man climbed her hair with trembling arms, and when he reached the top and their eyes met, both of them were changed.\n\nHe came back night after night. They talked for hours. He told her about the world outside — forests and markets and music and people and sky that went on forever.\n\nWhen the witch discovered them, she cut Rapunzel\'s hair and sent her far away. The prince fell from the tower into the thorns below, and for a long while both of them were lost.\n\nBut love that is real has a way of finding.\n\nWhen Rapunzel\'s tears fell on his eyes, he saw again — and when he looked up, she was there.\n\nThey walked out of the forest side by side, and Rapunzel felt, for the first time, the wide soft ground beneath her own two feet.',
        duration: 5,
        rating: 4.9,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/Luna with Magical Hair.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['adventure', 'true love', 'freedom'],
        isFeatured: false,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '43',
        title: 'Cinderella',
        category: 'Fairy Tales',
        description:
            'Cinderella lived in a house that had once been full of love, but love had gone out of it the way warmth leaves a room — slowly, then all at once.\n\nHer stepmother gave orders. Her stepsisters took everything. Cinderella swept and stitched and scrubbed, and kept her heart quietly to herself.\n\nWhen the royal ball was announced, she watched her stepfamily leave in silk and pearls and did not cry. She simply sat by the cold fireplace.\n\nAnd then — light. And the warm smell of something kind in the air.\n\nHer fairy godmother came not with grand speeches but with a practical sort of magic: a coach, a gown, glass slippers that fit like they had been made for her — because they had.\n\n"Be home by midnight," the fairy godmother said. "Not a moment later."\n\nAt the ball, the prince saw her across the room and walked straight toward her, and they danced until the clock began to strike.\n\nShe fled. She lost a slipper. She did not look back.\n\nBut glass slippers only fit one person in the world.\n\nAnd when the prince knelt before her in her dusty kitchen and the slipper slid onto her foot, Cinderella looked at him — not at the crown, not at the palace — and knew that he had come for her.',
        duration: 7,
        rating: 5.0,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/Cinderella.png',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['magic', 'dreams', 'true love'],
        isFeatured: true,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '44',
        title: 'Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs',
        category: 'Fairy Tales',
        description:
            'Snow White had a face that the mirror always told the truth about, which is why the Queen hated her.\n\nWhen the huntsman could not bring himself to carry out the Queen\'s order, he led Snow White to the edge of the forest and told her to run. She ran without stopping until the trees grew kinder and the paths grew softer, and she found herself at a tiny door.\n\nInside: seven small beds, seven small chairs, seven small bowls on the table.\n\nThe seven dwarfs came home that evening to find her sleeping across three of their beds, her dark hair spread on the pillow.\n\nThey let her stay.\n\nFor a while it was good — the small warm cottage, the forest, the work and the laughter. But the Queen\'s mirror never forgot. Three times she came in disguise, and the third time, the poisoned apple found its mark.\n\nSnow White fell into a sleep that looked, from the outside, just like death.\n\nThe dwarfs could not bear to bury her. They kept her in a glass case in the forest.\n\nWhen the prince found her there and the kiss broke the spell, Snow White opened her eyes not to a stranger\'s face, but to a world that had been waiting — patiently, faithfully — for her to come back to it.',
        duration: 7,
        rating: 5.0,
        imageUrl: 'assets/images/Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs.webp',
        audioUrl: 'assets/audio/stories/story-placeholder.mp3',
        tags: ['friendship', 'true love', 'kindness'],
        isFeatured: true,
      ),
      Story(
        id: '45',
        title: 'Sleeping Beauty',
