            'On the day Princess Aurora was born, the whole kingdom celebrated. Good fairies came with gifts of beauty and grace and a voice like birdsong. But one fairy — old and bitter and forgotten — came last with a curse: on her sixteenth birthday, Aurora would prick her finger on a spindle and die.\n\nThe last good fairy could not undo the curse, but she could soften it: Aurora would not die, but sleep — a deep and dreamless sleep — until true love\'s kiss woke her.\n\nHer parents burned every spindle in the kingdom. They kept her safe and happy and never spoke of curses.\n\nBut some things find their way.\n\nOn her sixteenth birthday, Aurora found a spinning wheel in a forgotten tower — and touched the spindle.\n\nThe whole castle sighed and slept.\n\nThick vines crept over the walls. A hundred years passed outside, light and dark, light and dark.\n\nA prince who had heard the old story fought through the thorns not knowing if it was real, only knowing he had to try.\n\nHe found her in the tower, still and pale.\n\nHe knelt beside her.\n\nHe kissed her.\n\nAurora\'s eyes opened — to the prince\'s face, to sunlight through the window, to a world that had held its breath a hundred years, waiting to begin again.',
